    {
        "content": "<p>Is this true? I thought that in the 1500s they had examples of cubics with a real root but for which the only way to \"solve it by radicals\" was to use complex numbers.</p>",
        "id": 521030826,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1748501071
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Like if you have some cubic polynomial with Galois group <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A_3</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">3</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> then it's not clear to me that you can get the roots of that cubic just by taking n'th roots whilst staying in that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>A</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A_3</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">3</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> extension. You can't take square roots for degree reasons, and taking a cube root will give you a non-Galois degree 3 extension because you don't have cube roots of unity. However once you allow yourself some extra room you can find the root, because the moment you add a cube root of unity then the extension is a Kummer extension so can be obtained by adjoining a cube root.</p>",
        "id": 521031244,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1748501293
    },
